,"1152":"1152","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1180":"1180"},"en":{"1172–Deceased":"1172–Deceased","1172–Female":"1172–Deceased","1160–1190":"1160–1190","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1146–Male":"1146–Deceased","1152–1173":"1152–1173","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1152":"1152","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harcourt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the places in Eure and Calvados named Harcourt, from Old French <i>cour(t)</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (see   Court  ) with an obscure first element. This surname is very rare in France.","English: habitational name from either of two places in Shropshire named Harcourt. The one near Cleobury Mortimer gets the name from Old English <i>heafocere</i> ‘hawker, falconer’ + <i>cot</i> ‘hut, cottage’; the one near Wem has as its first element Old English <i>hearpere</i> (see   Harper  ).","History: The surname of French origin (see 1 above) is listed along with the equally rare or even extinct variants or altered forms <i>Haraucourt</i>, <i>Herancourt</i>, and <i>Héraucourt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Court","meanings":["English: topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>curt</i>, <i>court</i> ‘large house’ (a word of the same ultimately Latin origin as 2 below), denoting someone who lived or worked in a manor house or castle, a courtly retainer.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (from Latin <i>cohors</i>, <i>cors</i>, genitive <i>cohortis</i>, <i>cortis</i> ‘court, farmyard, enclosure’).","English and French: nickname for a physically small man, or ironically for a large man, from the adjective Middle English <i>curt</i>, Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘short, small’ (from Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘curtailed, truncated, cut short, broken off’). Compare French   Lecourt  ."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":43,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":52,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":87,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma de Harcourt was born in 1172, her father, Sir Walter Harcourt, was 27 and her mother, Alice de Noel, was 21. She married John Bradshaw de Sayer IV in 1180, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1172–Deceased":"1172–Surnud","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","1160–1190":"1160–1190","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1146–Male":"1146–Surnud","1152–1173":"1152–1173","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1152":"1152","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1180":"1180"},"fi":{"1172–Deceased":"1172–Kuollut","1172–Female":"1172–Kuollut","1160–1190":"1160–1190","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1146–Male":"1146–Kuollut","1152–1173":"1152–1173","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1152":"1152","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1180":"1180"},"fr":{"1172–Deceased":"1172–Décédée","1172–Female":"1172–Décédée","1160–1190":"1160–1190","1180–Male":"1180–Décédé","1146–Male":"1146–Décédé","1152–1173":"1152–1173","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1152":"1152","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Emma de Harcourt est née en 1172, son père, Sir Walter Harcourt, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Ali